WEBVTT

00:03.699 --> 00:04.047
.

00:04.091 --> 00:06.093
- Okay, home stretch, Luna.

00:06.136 --> 00:08.443
We just need to find
Dada's other shoe.

00:08.486 --> 00:10.749
Did you steal Dada's shoe?

00:10.793 --> 00:11.924
No? Well, that's nice of you.

00:11.968 --> 00:14.840
Where is it? Where's my shoe?

00:14.884 --> 00:16.842
Shoe, shoe, shoe. Shoe!

00:16.886 --> 00:19.062
Luna, shoe!

00:19.106 --> 00:20.585
And--

00:20.629 --> 00:21.760
oh, yogurt.

00:21.804 --> 00:23.110
[knocking on door]

00:23.153 --> 00:27.027
Uh, hey, hey, hey, hey.

00:27.070 --> 00:28.419
Hey! Thank you guys so much.

00:28.463 --> 00:30.334
I know it's last minute.
- Oh, no worries.

00:30.378 --> 00:32.815
- My Tuesday nanny
just canceled on me.

00:32.858 --> 00:34.686
I didn't have anyone.
- What is that smell?

00:34.730 --> 00:36.210
- Oh, uh, fun fact,

00:36.253 --> 00:38.168
when Luna's waffle gets stuck
in the toaster too long

00:38.212 --> 00:39.126
it becomes a charcoal
briquette.

00:39.169 --> 00:40.431
I'll get that for you.

00:40.475 --> 00:42.172
- I think I smell
something else.

00:42.216 --> 00:43.913
- Yeah, that's her,
uh, lo mein.

00:43.956 --> 00:46.089
She really likes it spicy.
- Takeout for breakfast.

00:46.133 --> 00:49.179
- Uh, well,
it's usually milk and eggs

00:49.223 --> 00:51.486
but we are out of milk.

00:51.529 --> 00:52.443
Also eggs.

00:52.487 --> 00:54.532
So I tried to do
the waffle thing

00:54.576 --> 00:56.621
but that turned
into a briquette.

00:56.665 --> 00:57.883
So, I, uh, yeah.

00:57.927 --> 00:58.884
It was either lo mein or soup.

00:58.928 --> 01:00.190
Could you guys do a quick favor

01:00.234 --> 01:01.539
and go to the grocery store?

01:01.583 --> 01:04.064
We just need milk and eggs
and, uh, waffles.

01:05.239 --> 01:06.370
- Come on, sweetheart.

01:06.414 --> 01:07.893
Grandma's gonna
get you changed.

01:07.937 --> 01:09.330
- Hey.

01:09.373 --> 01:11.114
[gasps]
You got a double kiss!

01:11.158 --> 01:13.377
- Oh, and wipes?
- Wipes, yes. We need wipes.

01:13.421 --> 01:16.119
Thank you so much.
Best grandparents ever.

01:16.163 --> 01:18.817
The stuff of legends. Yes!

01:18.861 --> 01:20.167
Luna, I love you.

01:20.210 --> 01:23.213
Okay, thank you, guys.
Seriously. Bye.

01:23.257 --> 01:25.346
- [exhales]
Wow.

01:25.389 --> 01:28.566
[upbeat music]

01:28.610 --> 01:30.220
♪

01:30.264 --> 01:33.049
- ♪ Nobody gonna
bring me down ♪

01:33.093 --> 01:36.139
♪ Been running
since I hit the ground ♪

01:36.183 --> 01:38.968
♪ Try to catch me if you can

01:39.011 --> 01:41.188
♪ Most people
don't understand ♪

01:41.231 --> 01:43.103
- We need to talk about this.
- ♪ I'm a rebel

01:43.146 --> 01:45.105
- Harper, turn it down!
- ♪ I'm on another level

01:45.148 --> 01:46.889
- I put that in the closet.

01:46.932 --> 01:49.239
- And I took it back out.

01:49.283 --> 01:50.893
We need to talk about him, Ig.

01:50.936 --> 01:53.200
- Yeah, we will.

01:53.243 --> 01:55.419
- What? You've been
saying that for a week.

01:56.899 --> 01:59.293
Have you thought about a 21/20?
- No.

01:59.336 --> 02:01.686
I mean, yes, I've thought
about a 21/20, obviously.

02:01.730 --> 02:03.471
But that's a psychiatric hold,
it's not--

02:03.514 --> 02:04.863
- It would keep Chance
off the street

02:04.907 --> 02:07.518
and away from our kids.
- For 72 hours.

02:07.562 --> 02:09.999
And then he'd be back on
the streets, feeling betrayed.

02:10.042 --> 02:11.609
- Okay, fine.

02:11.653 --> 02:13.394
Then go for something
more permanent.

02:13.437 --> 02:15.483
- No, Martin,
I am not discussing

02:15.526 --> 02:17.180
a restraining order with you.

02:19.226 --> 02:20.357
Hey.

02:20.401 --> 02:22.620
Hi, babe. Hi.

02:22.664 --> 02:24.405
Everything's fine, okay?
We're just discussing some

02:24.448 --> 02:25.884
boring old grown up stuff.

02:25.928 --> 02:27.799
Why don't you go back up
and log in to school, okay?

02:27.843 --> 02:29.192
I'll meet you there.

02:29.236 --> 02:30.498
It's okay. Go for it.

02:31.847 --> 02:33.153
And music off, sweetie.

02:36.504 --> 02:38.854
That is exactly why I didn't
want to discuss this, okay?

02:38.897 --> 02:40.638
A restraining order
is a formal connection

02:40.682 --> 02:42.205
between Chance and I.
It's what he wants.

02:42.249 --> 02:44.686
- All that matters
is they reduce risk.

02:44.729 --> 02:46.383
- [sighs]

02:46.427 --> 02:48.124
Sometimes.
- Most times.

02:48.168 --> 02:49.865
And they got
a way better track record

02:49.908 --> 02:51.214
than wishful thinking.

02:51.258 --> 02:52.476
- If we provoke Chance,
he could hurt himself.

02:52.520 --> 02:54.739
- This is not about Chance.

02:54.783 --> 02:56.001
This is about us.

02:56.045 --> 02:57.873
Our safety, our kids.

02:59.353 --> 03:01.224
Look, we... [sighs]

03:01.268 --> 03:03.095
No, you know what, Iggy?

03:03.139 --> 03:04.575
You have to do something.

03:04.619 --> 03:05.533
Today.

03:09.711 --> 03:12.366
- What? I don't want that.
- It's just oat milk.

03:12.409 --> 03:13.715
- What you mean,
"just oat milk"?

03:13.758 --> 03:15.238
You ever seen
an udder on an oat?

03:15.282 --> 03:16.848
That's not natural.
- Natural?

03:16.892 --> 03:18.372
A few minutes ago
you were just raving

03:18.415 --> 03:20.678
about some beer
made out of oysters?

03:20.722 --> 03:22.898
- Oyster stout is normal beer

03:22.941 --> 03:25.466
made from the shells
of oysters. It's--

03:25.509 --> 03:26.641
- And I've yet
to meet a mollusk

03:26.684 --> 03:28.295
made out of grain,
hops, or yeast.

03:28.338 --> 03:30.210
- All right, look, that's it.
I'm--I'm gonna take you out

03:30.253 --> 03:32.212
to have that beer tonight.

03:34.039 --> 03:36.259
Oh, no. I--I'm--

03:36.303 --> 03:37.260
I'm sorry. Not like that.

03:37.304 --> 03:39.871
I wasn't trying to make a move.

03:39.915 --> 03:41.569
- Uh-huh.

03:41.612 --> 03:43.179
- I can't be home tonight.

03:43.223 --> 03:46.269
You know, I'm trying to think
of a reason to stay out.

03:46.313 --> 03:48.140
- Why's that?
- You know, my--

03:48.184 --> 03:51.492
my roommate is having
a gentleman over for a "visit."

03:51.535 --> 03:54.059
- You have a roommate?

03:54.103 --> 03:56.061
- Yeah, my mom.

03:56.105 --> 03:58.238
My roommate is my mother.

03:58.281 --> 04:00.588
- You live with your mom?

04:00.631 --> 04:02.851
And your mom is the one
hanging the sock on the door.

04:04.418 --> 04:06.550
- So now we're clowning?
Is that it?

04:06.594 --> 04:08.378
- Yeah, you definitely
were not making a move.

04:08.422 --> 04:09.553
[chuckles]
- See, now, that--

04:09.597 --> 04:12.513
that's the way--
now you owe me a drink.

04:12.556 --> 04:14.341
- Fine, I know
the perfect place.

04:14.384 --> 04:16.734
I will text you the address.
- Okay.

04:24.002 --> 04:26.570
- Helen. Hey, uh,

04:26.614 --> 04:27.571
hey.

04:28.877 --> 04:31.445
What do you need?
- Uh, nothing.

04:31.488 --> 04:33.185
I just saw you
walking down the hallway

04:33.229 --> 04:34.970
and it looked like more fun
than my hallway so--

04:35.013 --> 04:37.059
- Okay.

04:37.102 --> 04:39.931
- You okay? Um, work, life?

04:39.975 --> 04:41.585
- It's good. All good.
- All good.

04:41.629 --> 04:42.586
What's with the rosary?

04:42.630 --> 04:44.066
- It's not a rosary.

04:44.109 --> 04:45.502
- Yeah? Uh, well, you know,

04:45.546 --> 04:47.417
if it looks like a rosary
and smells like a rosary--

04:47.461 --> 04:49.724
- It's personal.

04:49.767 --> 04:51.421
- I don't think
that's how it goes.

04:54.816 --> 04:56.905
- You're actually
considering it?

04:56.948 --> 04:59.081
Leaving New Amsterdam?
- Hey, it's a good gig.

04:59.124 --> 05:01.518
More money, less drama.
Plus, I could walk to work.

05:01.562 --> 05:03.651
Plus, it is Mt. Zion.

05:03.694 --> 05:05.130
- [in English accent]
Oh, I'm Casey,

05:05.174 --> 05:07.785
and I want to work at a big,
posh, private hospital

05:07.829 --> 05:09.787
where nothing exciting
ever happens.

05:09.831 --> 05:11.354
- Whatever.
Your accent's wack.

05:11.398 --> 05:13.051
- Incoming!

05:13.095 --> 05:14.662
Bertha James, 64 years old.

05:14.705 --> 05:16.968
Accidental impalement
on pruning shears.

05:17.012 --> 05:20.450
BP 138 over 74
and slightly tachy at 114.

05:20.494 --> 05:21.973
- [groans]
- Already vaccinated for COVID.

05:22.017 --> 05:23.279
- Okay, let's get her
to Bay 24.

05:23.323 --> 05:26.543
- Just get these things
out of me!

05:26.587 --> 05:29.067
- We will, but first
you need a CAT scan and work-up

05:29.111 --> 05:31.592
so we can figure out the safest
way to remove them, okay?

05:31.635 --> 05:34.246
How bad is the pain?

05:34.290 --> 05:36.597
- Bad!
- Okay, uh, Turan,

05:36.640 --> 05:38.250
can I get, um--what the--

05:38.294 --> 05:40.514
[metal creaking, crashing]

05:40.557 --> 05:42.994
[all exclaiming]

05:43.038 --> 05:45.083
- [screaming]
- Is everybody okay?

05:45.127 --> 05:47.651
You okay? Everybody okay?
We need help over here!

05:47.695 --> 05:49.174
- What the hell is going on
in here?

05:49.218 --> 05:50.654
- Let's pull them out.
Let's get them out of here.

05:50.698 --> 05:53.353
Okay, get maintenance
down here now.

05:53.396 --> 05:54.963
- Are you kidding me!?

05:55.006 --> 05:57.835
- Feel the excitement.
- Excitement?

05:57.879 --> 06:00.534
- Okay, let's get them
out of here.

06:00.577 --> 06:02.840
- So great to see you all
in the flesh again.

06:02.884 --> 06:05.277
Mask-less, here we are.
[group laughing]

06:05.321 --> 06:06.496
You know, virtual visits
were great.

06:06.540 --> 06:08.585
What a great tool
we got to use but, man,

06:08.629 --> 06:10.152
have I missed in-person

06:10.195 --> 06:12.154
inpatient visiting days.
These are the best.

06:12.197 --> 06:14.374
I mean, families coming
together, reconnecting.

06:14.417 --> 06:16.201
This is why we do
what we do, right?

06:16.245 --> 06:18.073
- Are gifts okay?

06:18.116 --> 06:19.291
- Yeah.

06:19.335 --> 06:22.382
- 'Cause I, uh,
brought my son a journal.

06:22.425 --> 06:23.861
- Great, yeah, journal.
Good call.

06:23.905 --> 06:25.863
Anything that encourages
expression, I'm all for it.

06:25.907 --> 06:28.213
- Yeah, but the orderly
confiscated it.

06:28.257 --> 06:30.433
- Ahh, yeah...

06:30.477 --> 06:32.609
spiral-bound, I'm guessing?

06:32.653 --> 06:34.829
Yeah, okay, good segue.

06:34.872 --> 06:36.439
Couple ground rules
we should talk about.

06:36.483 --> 06:38.615
No sharp objects
are allowed inside.

06:38.659 --> 06:41.879
Anything spiral-bound,
jewelry, earrings.

06:41.923 --> 06:44.316
Um, anything that
a child inclined to self-harm

06:44.360 --> 06:46.101
would or could self-harm with.

06:46.144 --> 06:47.929
Um, also,

06:47.972 --> 06:50.453
no outside medication
is allowed in, okay?

06:50.497 --> 06:51.715
So any pills
that you came with,

06:51.759 --> 06:52.716
you can leave them with me.

06:52.760 --> 06:54.065
You get them when you leave.

06:54.109 --> 06:55.197
Uh...

06:55.240 --> 06:57.460
[emotional music]

06:57.504 --> 06:58.896
but, guys, that's not--that's--

06:58.940 --> 07:00.376
hey, that's not what
today is about, all right?

07:00.420 --> 07:02.987
Today is about progress.
Your kids are getting better.

07:03.031 --> 07:05.773
They're getting better
every day and in a few moments,

07:05.816 --> 07:08.123
you are going to see that
with your very own eyes, so.

07:08.166 --> 07:10.255
- You can bring your son
my cookies, if you want.

07:10.299 --> 07:11.474
I made way too many.

07:11.518 --> 07:13.389
- Yes, that is
the spirit right there.

07:13.433 --> 07:14.521
Okay, guys, what do you think?

07:14.564 --> 07:16.261
Want to go see your kiddos?

07:16.305 --> 07:17.611
Let's go! Follow me.

07:22.529 --> 07:24.269
- DeMarcus Lott, 27.

07:24.313 --> 07:25.749
Taxi-to-bike head-on collision.

07:25.793 --> 07:26.794
- Whoa, whoa, whoa!

07:26.837 --> 07:28.578
- What the hell happened here?

07:28.622 --> 07:30.537
- Emergency bowel disimpaction

07:30.580 --> 07:32.495
of the building's
old drainage pipes.

07:32.539 --> 07:34.584
- Crap.
- Well, let's hope not.

07:34.628 --> 07:36.804
Uh, Mr. Lott,
how are you feeling?

07:36.847 --> 07:38.283
- Like I'm about
to be Internet famous.

07:38.327 --> 07:40.242
Check this out.
Tossed off the hood of the car,

07:40.285 --> 07:43.375
rebounded off the mailbox,
landed smack on the pavement.

07:43.419 --> 07:45.290
That's why you wear a GoPro.

07:45.334 --> 07:46.727
- And a helmet.

07:46.770 --> 07:51.122
Brunstetter, let's order
a CT scan for Mr. Lott.

07:51.166 --> 07:52.950
- Any more openings
at Mt. Zion?

07:52.994 --> 07:54.212
- Heard that.

07:56.127 --> 07:57.868
- Dr. Bloom.

07:57.912 --> 07:59.653
- Damn it, she's tachypneic.

08:04.614 --> 08:07.530
Okay, let's get her
on nasal cannula O2.

08:07.574 --> 08:08.836
- It was the shears?

08:08.879 --> 08:10.402
- Nowhere near her heart
or her lungs.

08:10.446 --> 08:12.013
- Hello?

08:12.056 --> 08:14.102
Somebody?

08:14.145 --> 08:16.104
What's this on my leg?
You see this?

08:17.801 --> 08:20.151
- I got that on my arm.

08:20.195 --> 08:23.154
[ominous music]

08:23.198 --> 08:25.635
- [wheezy coughing]

08:25.679 --> 08:32.816
♪

08:34.339 --> 08:35.558
[coughing]

08:35.602 --> 08:40.258
[metallic plinking]

08:40.302 --> 08:42.043
- We need to evacuate the ED.

08:42.086 --> 08:43.392
- Evacuate? Why?

08:43.435 --> 08:46.830
- That's not dirty water.
That's a chemical spill.

08:50.268 --> 08:50.486
.

08:50.530 --> 08:53.097
- Okay, the sickest patients
and those with the most

08:53.141 --> 08:54.621
chemical exposure
go to the front of the line

08:54.664 --> 08:57.101
for DECON showers, chest CTs,
and arterial blood gases.

08:57.145 --> 08:58.625
Less acute
are gonna have to wait.

08:58.668 --> 09:00.452
Uh, Mrs. Westbrook,
how you feeling?

09:00.496 --> 09:02.324
- Better.
- Blood sugar's down to 187.

09:02.367 --> 09:03.368
Okay, that's what
I like to hear.

09:03.412 --> 09:04.761
Low exposure, back of the line.

09:04.805 --> 09:07.982
- Dr. Bloom, I ran
the symptoms by Poison Control

09:08.025 --> 09:09.592
and they suspect
herbicide called

09:09.636 --> 09:12.334
4-methyl-2-chlorophenoxyacetic
acid.

09:12.377 --> 09:14.815
Apparently,
MFCA is odorless, colorless,

09:14.858 --> 09:16.077
and highly corrosive.

09:16.120 --> 09:17.774
- Huh, what a great trio.

09:17.818 --> 09:20.124
- Coming through.
- I put the ED on diversion

09:20.168 --> 09:23.388
and activated HazMat protocol.
- HazMat!?

09:23.432 --> 09:25.260
- Busted pipe doused
Bertha pretty bad.

09:25.303 --> 09:28.045
- Into the open wound?
- Direct hit.

09:28.089 --> 09:29.438
- Since then,
she's been tachy with runs

09:29.481 --> 09:30.918
of wide complex V-tach.

09:30.961 --> 09:33.224
- Not to mention
the gardening shears

09:33.268 --> 09:35.531
still sticking out of me.
- We're gonna get to those.

09:35.575 --> 09:37.489
But first we gotta take care
of your heart and lungs.

09:37.533 --> 09:39.535
Which means a DECON shower

09:39.579 --> 09:41.232
to get the chemicals
off your skin.

09:41.276 --> 09:42.756
And then some wound irrigation

09:42.799 --> 09:44.714
to get the rest of it
out of your insides, all right?

09:44.758 --> 09:46.020
Just try to breathe.

09:46.063 --> 09:47.761
- Bertha's in,
but we only have two showers.

09:47.804 --> 09:49.545
It's gonna take hours
to get everyone through.

09:49.589 --> 09:51.591
- Okay, HazMat's bringing
more tents with more showers.

09:51.634 --> 09:53.157
Until then, we just
need to hold on.

09:53.201 --> 09:55.507
- I'm gonna go find where
an herbicide banned in the '70s

09:55.551 --> 09:57.161
is hiding in our hospital.

09:57.205 --> 10:00.121
[tense music]

10:00.164 --> 10:03.864
♪

10:03.907 --> 10:06.388
[elevator dings]

10:06.431 --> 10:08.216
- Oh, just who
I was looking for.

10:08.259 --> 10:09.870
- Dora, the HCC heard about

10:09.913 --> 10:11.088
our chemical spill, I take it?

10:11.132 --> 10:13.090
- And I need an important file

10:13.134 --> 10:14.701
the medical director
should have on hand.

10:14.744 --> 10:15.876
[phone beeps]
- Well, then you need to talk

10:15.919 --> 10:17.355
to the medical director.

10:17.399 --> 10:19.444
- Because Max would know
where any important files are?

10:19.488 --> 10:20.402
I'm betting
I'll have better odds

10:20.445 --> 10:21.490
with his former number two.

10:21.533 --> 10:22.752
- All right,
what are we looking for?

10:22.796 --> 10:25.799
- Hazardous material
inspection reports.

10:25.842 --> 10:28.453
If we were briefed

10:28.497 --> 10:31.674
on any MFCA storage issues,
then we're liable.

10:31.718 --> 10:33.415
- The ED ceiling caved in

10:33.458 --> 10:34.895
and poured poison
all over our patients.

10:34.938 --> 10:37.332
I'm pretty sure we're liable.

10:37.375 --> 10:39.682
- Just find the report.

10:39.726 --> 10:40.814
I'm just doing my job.

10:42.903 --> 10:44.687
[smashing]

10:44.731 --> 10:47.647
- The MFCA has branched
into all these pipes.

10:47.690 --> 10:50.519
Corrosion's not as bad
as the ED.

10:50.562 --> 10:51.825
- You get a flood
of that stuff,

10:51.868 --> 10:53.565
all these pipes will go.
- And then instead

10:53.609 --> 10:55.132
of one chemical spill,
we'll have 50.

10:55.176 --> 10:56.307
It's gotta be
coming from somewhere.

10:56.351 --> 10:57.831
We'll split up
and we find the source.

10:57.874 --> 11:00.398
[smashing]

11:00.442 --> 11:03.619
[tense music]

11:03.663 --> 11:07.928
♪

11:07.971 --> 11:10.539
- The protection order will
legally compel Chance Becker

11:10.582 --> 11:12.715
to stay away from you,
your workplace, and your home.

11:12.759 --> 11:14.499
He'll be prohibited
from any direct contact

11:14.543 --> 11:16.676
with you or your family.

11:16.719 --> 11:18.155
The court may add exceptions,

11:18.199 --> 11:20.114
but I've been in-house counsel
here a long time,

11:20.157 --> 11:21.376
there won't be any issues.

11:21.419 --> 11:23.291
- Do we need
to inform anyone internally?

11:23.334 --> 11:24.466
- No, only if you want us to.

11:24.509 --> 11:25.815
- I think I'd like
to keep it quiet.

11:25.859 --> 11:27.991
You know, for Chance's sake.

11:28.035 --> 11:29.384
- For Chance?

11:29.427 --> 11:32.300
- Yeah, um--
- Anne.

11:33.605 --> 11:35.695
- Uh, Neil,
if you'll excuse me.

11:35.738 --> 11:37.697
Thank you, thank you very much.

11:37.740 --> 11:39.220
Hey, Anne, Julie.

11:39.263 --> 11:40.482
Hey, guys, wait up.

11:40.525 --> 11:42.005
Whoa, what's the matter?

11:42.049 --> 11:43.485
What happened?
Something happen with your son?

11:43.528 --> 11:44.834
- Alex just got upset.

11:44.878 --> 11:46.662
- Upset? He was screaming.

11:46.706 --> 11:48.490
He was completely
out of control.

11:48.533 --> 11:50.057
- Okay, well, why don't we all

11:50.100 --> 11:51.406
go have a chat in my office

11:51.449 --> 11:52.581
and we'll figure it out.
- What's there to say?

11:52.624 --> 11:53.800
He doesn't want us here,
so we're leaving.

11:53.843 --> 11:55.323
- Well, that's a bit
of a hasty reaction.

11:55.366 --> 11:56.716
- Sorry folks,
we're shutting the exits.

11:56.759 --> 11:58.413
There's been a chemical spill
downstairs.

11:58.456 --> 12:00.284
No one in or out
until it's safe.

12:00.328 --> 12:02.156
- But the kids--
- Everybody's fine up here.

12:02.199 --> 12:03.461
I just need you to hold tight

12:03.505 --> 12:04.941
until the downstairs exit's
decontaminated.

12:04.985 --> 12:06.464
- Okay.

12:06.508 --> 12:08.379
Okay, thank you. Um...

12:10.120 --> 12:13.950
Well, since we're
all stuck here...

12:13.994 --> 12:16.779
come on, let's have a chat.

12:16.823 --> 12:18.433
Come on, let's go.

12:18.476 --> 12:21.392
[punchy drum beat]

12:21.436 --> 12:23.568
♪

12:23.612 --> 12:26.397
- Couple more should do it.

12:26.441 --> 12:28.704
- Take your time.

12:28.748 --> 12:31.228
Certainly, don't worry
about the shears.

12:32.577 --> 12:34.797
- We haven't forgotten,
I promise.

12:34.841 --> 12:36.843
♪

12:36.886 --> 12:38.714
- No rush.

12:38.758 --> 12:40.237
- Once we stabilize
your vitals,

12:40.281 --> 12:41.499
they are coming out.

12:41.543 --> 12:42.544
- Would you like
more pain meds?

12:42.587 --> 12:44.851
- What I'd like is a hospital

12:44.894 --> 12:46.722
that's not falling apart.

12:46.766 --> 12:49.507
I mean, how can you even
see what you're doing

12:49.551 --> 12:51.248
when the lights keep dimming?

12:51.292 --> 12:53.120
It's like a cavern in here.

12:53.163 --> 12:55.731
- The lights aren't dimming.

12:55.775 --> 12:58.386
- But why is everything
getting darker?

12:58.429 --> 13:01.432
[tense music]

13:01.476 --> 13:05.654
♪

13:05.697 --> 13:08.744
[slamming]

13:08.788 --> 13:11.747
[liquid dripping]

13:11.791 --> 13:18.667
♪

13:18.710 --> 13:21.583
- You ever heard of MFCA
exposure causing blindness?

13:21.626 --> 13:23.585
- I'd barely even heard of MFCA

13:23.628 --> 13:25.369
before it gushed
all over my ED.

13:25.413 --> 13:26.718
- Well, Bertha's
now experiencing

13:26.762 --> 13:28.677
complete and total vision loss.

13:28.720 --> 13:30.200
- She did take the biggest hit.

13:30.244 --> 13:31.854
Had the most extreme exposure.

13:31.898 --> 13:33.943
- Well, I put her on dialysis
to try to clean the toxins

13:33.987 --> 13:35.771
out of her blood but, look,

13:35.815 --> 13:37.860
if this is blinding people,
then we need to get

13:37.904 --> 13:39.862
everybody decontaminated
as soon as possible.

13:39.906 --> 13:41.168
- Oh, yeah,
'cause up until now,

13:41.211 --> 13:42.256
we've been dragging our feet.

13:42.299 --> 13:43.431
- Hey, look, I'm just saying

13:43.474 --> 13:44.606
there could be more surprises.

13:44.649 --> 13:46.826
- Got it. Thank you.

13:46.869 --> 13:53.789
♪

13:55.486 --> 13:57.097
Let's get this line moving,
people.

13:57.140 --> 13:58.838
Come on.

13:58.881 --> 14:05.845
♪

14:09.500 --> 14:12.547
[light flickering and buzzing]

14:15.332 --> 14:22.339
♪

14:22.383 --> 14:25.952
[liquid splashing and hissing]

14:25.995 --> 14:28.955
[foreboding music]

14:28.998 --> 14:35.918
♪

14:40.880 --> 14:43.839
[metallic groan]

14:43.883 --> 14:46.886
[rumbling]

14:48.844 --> 14:52.239
[drain slurping]

14:52.282 --> 14:53.980
[groaning and hissing]

14:54.023 --> 14:56.939
[liquid rushing]

15:01.204 --> 15:02.727
- Come on!

15:05.339 --> 15:06.993
Help!

15:07.036 --> 15:08.908
[liquid dripping]

15:08.951 --> 15:11.301
Help!

15:11.345 --> 15:13.303
I need some help in here!

15:13.347 --> 15:15.915
Anybody! Help!

15:19.309 --> 15:19.483
.

15:19.527 --> 15:20.484
- Max, Sandra Fall and I

15:20.528 --> 15:22.269
have been looking everywhere
for the hazardous materials

15:22.312 --> 15:24.488
inspection report
that you should've filed.

15:24.532 --> 15:26.186
But of course,
it's nowhere to be found.

15:26.229 --> 15:28.275
Much like yourself.
Where are you?

15:28.318 --> 15:29.667
Call me, please.

15:29.711 --> 15:32.627
[tense music]

15:32.670 --> 15:35.108
- Miguel, do you know where
Dr. Goodwin went after this?

15:35.151 --> 15:36.631
- They just called me
for clean-up.

15:36.674 --> 15:37.849
- Right.

15:49.557 --> 15:52.560
[gripping music]

15:52.603 --> 15:54.649
- Ah, bike man, good news.

15:54.692 --> 15:56.694
Your CT came back clear.

15:56.738 --> 15:59.654
I'd prescribe Advil
and a brake on that Fixie.

15:59.697 --> 16:01.003
- So I'm good to go?
- Ah, no.

16:01.047 --> 16:02.744
Not until you go through DECON.

16:02.787 --> 16:04.224
- But I was barely in there.

16:04.267 --> 16:06.356
- Which is why I'm sending you
to the back of the line.

16:06.400 --> 16:12.058
♪

16:12.101 --> 16:14.582
Um, is the insulin
back in the ED?

16:14.625 --> 16:16.018
- Check over there.

16:16.062 --> 16:17.454
I put them in the crash cart

16:17.498 --> 16:19.979
but we're still moving stuff
out of the ED.

16:20.022 --> 16:23.721
- Ah, somebody is thinkin'.

16:23.765 --> 16:26.072
- Hey, you had
way more exposure

16:26.115 --> 16:27.812
than anyone else.
- And your point is?

16:27.856 --> 16:29.336
- You need to be the next one
into the DECON showers.

16:29.379 --> 16:31.338
- Okay, I don't know
how it works at Mt. Zion,

16:31.381 --> 16:33.296
but in my ED,
patients come first.

16:46.657 --> 16:49.791
- Oppositional defiant disorder
is tough.

16:49.834 --> 16:53.055
Kids with ODD like Alex
are rude.

16:53.099 --> 16:54.709
They're aggressive, vindictive.

16:54.752 --> 16:58.669
- Our son hates us, Dr. Frome.
- He doesn't--

16:58.713 --> 17:00.367
- You were there. You saw him.

17:00.410 --> 17:03.631
- No, no, listen to me.
It can feel a lot like hate.

17:03.674 --> 17:05.894
It can look exactly like hate.

17:05.937 --> 17:07.113
But it's not hate.

17:07.156 --> 17:10.986
It is brain function,
that's it.

17:11.030 --> 17:12.640
It's an inflated response

17:12.683 --> 17:14.120
to perceived threats.

17:14.163 --> 17:15.904
- And exactly how
did I threaten him?

17:15.947 --> 17:17.601
- You didn't.

17:17.645 --> 17:19.908
She didn't. I--

17:19.951 --> 17:21.083
I honestly think
this morning was just

17:21.127 --> 17:23.129
a low blood sugar moment.

17:23.172 --> 17:25.087
You know how he gets.

17:25.131 --> 17:27.785
[gentle music]

17:27.829 --> 17:30.092
I bet now that he's had
a minute, he'll be different.

17:30.136 --> 17:31.920
♪

17:31.963 --> 17:33.530
We should go back in
and try again.

17:33.574 --> 17:35.706
- No, actually, I don't think
that's a good idea.

17:35.750 --> 17:37.230
Julie...

17:37.273 --> 17:39.101
- Why not?
- Because I don't think that

17:39.145 --> 17:40.624
the problem today was Alex.

17:40.668 --> 17:42.235
♪

17:42.278 --> 17:46.674
I think that the real problem
is here, in this room.

17:46.717 --> 17:49.503
♪

17:49.546 --> 17:52.245
- You think Alex's ODD
is our fault?

17:52.288 --> 17:54.421
- No, ODD is no one's fault.

17:54.464 --> 17:56.858
I'm--I'm talking
specifically about

17:56.901 --> 17:58.207
what triggered Alex today.

17:58.251 --> 18:00.296
- And you think it was his moms

18:00.340 --> 18:02.081
bringing him cookies.

18:03.821 --> 18:06.085
I'm sorry.
I don't understand that at all.

18:06.128 --> 18:07.303
- Your wife does.

18:13.004 --> 18:14.441
- Anne?

18:16.312 --> 18:17.835
[emotional music]

18:17.879 --> 18:20.403
- Anne, look at where you are.

18:20.447 --> 18:22.057
Hiding the truth
is not working.

18:22.101 --> 18:29.195
♪

18:31.545 --> 18:34.069
- The two weeks that Alex
was out of the house...

18:34.113 --> 18:38.465
♪

18:38.508 --> 18:41.642
Have been the best two weeks
I've had in years.

18:41.685 --> 18:44.645
♪

18:44.688 --> 18:46.995
No screaming.

18:47.038 --> 18:48.953
No hitting.

18:48.997 --> 18:51.652
♪

18:51.695 --> 18:53.828
No one...

18:53.871 --> 18:57.353
attacking my beautiful wife...

18:57.397 --> 18:59.616
when she's just
trying to be nice.

18:59.660 --> 19:06.580
♪

19:10.018 --> 19:12.020
I didn't want to see him today.

19:12.063 --> 19:13.717
[breathes shakily]

19:13.761 --> 19:17.504
♪

19:17.547 --> 19:20.115
And on some level,
I think that he knows it.

19:20.159 --> 19:21.899
[sobs quietly]

19:21.943 --> 19:25.033
♪

19:25.076 --> 19:26.426
- Dialysis went great, Bertha.

19:26.469 --> 19:27.557
We're gonna give your sight

19:27.601 --> 19:29.385
a little more time
to reset, okay?

19:29.429 --> 19:33.389
- In the meantime,
I'll just lay here impaled.

19:33.433 --> 19:35.522
- [laughs]
Not at all.

19:35.565 --> 19:39.221
Look, next stop,
those shears are coming out.

19:39.265 --> 19:40.701
- [chuckles]

19:40.744 --> 19:43.312
I'm so sorry.

19:43.356 --> 19:45.271
None of this is your fault.

19:45.314 --> 19:47.011
- Don't worry about me.

19:47.055 --> 19:49.144
Just focus on you.

19:49.188 --> 19:52.234
- Focusing on me
is why I started gardening.

19:52.278 --> 19:53.888
My shrink said

19:53.931 --> 20:00.677
it's a way to tune everybody
else out and hear the universe.

20:00.721 --> 20:02.723
[chuckles]
I know, it's hippy.

20:02.766 --> 20:06.074
- [chuckles]
- But doesn't that sound nice?

20:06.117 --> 20:09.120
Hearing the universe.

20:09.164 --> 20:11.732
- It does.
- I'm trying to hear it now

20:11.775 --> 20:14.387
but these shears...

20:14.430 --> 20:17.041
makes it kinda har...

20:17.085 --> 20:18.739
[gurgles]

20:18.782 --> 20:21.089
[wheezing]

20:21.132 --> 20:22.569
[alarm beeping]
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

20:22.612 --> 20:24.571
Grab me two milligrams
of Ativan IV.

20:24.614 --> 20:26.225
- [choking]

20:26.268 --> 20:27.704
- Do we need to get
her back on dialysis?

20:27.748 --> 20:29.271
- It's too late, her body's
absorbed too much MFCA.

20:29.315 --> 20:31.142
- So where does that leave us?

20:31.186 --> 20:35.277
[alarm beeping]
- [choking]

20:35.321 --> 20:38.846
- Dr. Reynolds?

20:38.889 --> 20:40.456
- I--I don't know.

20:55.819 --> 20:57.821
- Max?

21:02.652 --> 21:04.785
- [faintly]
Anybody?

21:04.828 --> 21:07.657
- Max?

21:07.701 --> 21:09.746
- [faintly]
Help!

21:09.790 --> 21:11.574
[dramatic music]

21:11.618 --> 21:13.228
[liquid hissing]

21:13.272 --> 21:16.318
- Max?

21:16.362 --> 21:18.189
Max, you need
to get out of there.

21:18.233 --> 21:20.670
- I--I can't, I--I--

21:20.714 --> 21:22.716
if I let go of this,
the whole tank's gonna give.

21:22.759 --> 21:24.326
And it'd go
all over the hospital.

21:24.370 --> 21:25.806
Hundreds of people
are gonna be exposed.

21:25.849 --> 21:26.981
You need to go get help.

21:27.024 --> 21:30.376
- No, you're gonna leave.

21:30.419 --> 21:31.986
I'm gonna hold the pipe

21:32.029 --> 21:32.987
and you're gonna
go and get help.

21:33.030 --> 21:35.990
- I can't.
- Why not!?

21:36.033 --> 21:36.991
- I can't see.

21:37.034 --> 21:43.737
♪

21:48.785 --> 21:49.003
.

21:49.046 --> 21:50.700
- Anne, what you just described

21:50.744 --> 21:52.615
is a perfectly normal feeling.

21:52.659 --> 21:55.270
But Alex didn't erupt
this morning

21:55.314 --> 21:57.838
because you asked him
a question.

21:57.881 --> 21:59.361
Alex erupted

21:59.405 --> 22:03.452
because Julie stopped you
from disciplining him.

22:03.496 --> 22:05.019
And you just said that at home,

22:05.062 --> 22:07.674
Alex is triggered
by Julie just being nice.

22:11.025 --> 22:13.462
The threat that
Alex is perceiving

22:13.506 --> 22:15.638
is your positivity.

22:15.682 --> 22:17.727
- How can positivity
be a threat?

22:17.771 --> 22:19.642
- Well, Alex knows
that his troubles

22:19.686 --> 22:21.992
are deeper than blood sugar.

22:22.036 --> 22:23.820
And when you pretend
that they aren't,

22:23.864 --> 22:24.995
it scares him.

22:25.039 --> 22:26.823
It denies his reality.

22:26.867 --> 22:27.824
And Anne's, too.

22:27.868 --> 22:29.870
- [scoffs]

22:29.913 --> 22:34.265
♪

22:34.309 --> 22:35.397
You agree with him.

22:35.441 --> 22:42.404
♪

22:42.448 --> 22:44.841
Yes, I try to be positive.

22:44.885 --> 22:46.234
Alex can't. You won't.

22:46.277 --> 22:48.105
Somebody has to be.
- Why does somebody have to?

22:48.149 --> 22:50.064
Why can't we just acknowledge
what's actually happening?

22:50.107 --> 22:51.674
- You of all people
asking me that?

22:51.718 --> 22:53.720
The person who stood up
in front of all of us today

22:53.763 --> 22:55.199
like some camp counselor,

22:55.243 --> 22:57.419
acting like we weren't
all here to visit our kids

22:57.463 --> 22:58.855
in a mental hospital.

22:58.899 --> 23:00.814
Telling us, "Oh, it'll be
a great day today.

23:00.857 --> 23:02.206
"Just remember
to remove your jewelry

23:02.250 --> 23:04.470
so the kids don't try
and kill themselves."

23:04.513 --> 23:05.906
I'm denying reality?

23:05.949 --> 23:09.779
♪

23:09.823 --> 23:12.478
[monitor beeping]

23:15.394 --> 23:17.874
- You're actually
removing the shears?

23:17.918 --> 23:19.659
Floyd, it's too late for her.
She's dying.

23:19.702 --> 23:21.530
- Because of us.

23:21.574 --> 23:23.663
We did this to her.

23:23.706 --> 23:25.926
This hospital,
this--this building.

23:25.969 --> 23:27.536
♪

23:27.580 --> 23:29.190
You know, Bertha said that

23:29.233 --> 23:31.018
the shears were making it hard
for her to hear the universe.

23:31.061 --> 23:32.933
Well, if there's ever a time

23:32.976 --> 23:35.631
that we deserve
to hear the universe,

23:35.675 --> 23:37.938
it's when we're leaving it.

23:37.981 --> 23:41.855
♪

23:41.898 --> 23:44.771
[shower running]

23:44.814 --> 23:45.902
- Staff's all through.

23:45.946 --> 23:47.034
After Ms. Westbrook,

23:47.077 --> 23:48.209
it's just you
and DeMarcus Lott.

23:48.252 --> 23:49.906
- Where is he?
- He's around the corner,

23:49.950 --> 23:51.821
editing video
of his head-on collision.

23:55.738 --> 23:58.698
[foreboding music]

23:58.741 --> 24:05.835
♪

24:10.797 --> 24:13.669
- [wheezing gasps]

24:13.713 --> 24:16.237
- Mr. Lott?

24:16.280 --> 24:17.412
It's okay,
I've got you, DeMarcus.

24:17.456 --> 24:18.892
I got you, I got you,
I got you.

24:18.935 --> 24:22.852
- [wheezing]

24:22.896 --> 24:24.506
- I need help over here!

24:24.550 --> 24:26.203
Casey!

24:26.247 --> 24:28.597
A blood vessel
damaged in your accident

24:28.641 --> 24:30.033
must've just given way.

24:30.077 --> 24:31.905
It's caused
an expanding hematoma

24:31.948 --> 24:35.604
and it is closing off
your windpipe.

24:35.648 --> 24:37.432
I can fix it. I--I can fix it.

24:37.476 --> 24:39.826
I just gotta--just need to
drain the blood.

24:39.869 --> 24:41.567
Casey!

24:41.610 --> 24:43.612
[muffled]
Help, Casey!

24:43.656 --> 24:50.532
♪

24:54.928 --> 24:56.320
I need help!

24:56.364 --> 24:58.061
- [wheezing]

24:58.105 --> 25:03.545
♪

25:03.589 --> 25:05.808
[shoes squealing, thudding]

25:05.852 --> 25:07.636
- [groans]

25:07.680 --> 25:14.208
♪

25:14.251 --> 25:15.035
[grunts]

25:15.078 --> 25:22.216
♪

25:51.245 --> 25:54.857
[syringe squelching]

25:54.901 --> 25:56.729
[whispers tearfully]
Come on, come on.

25:56.772 --> 25:58.557
Come on, breathe. Come on.

25:58.600 --> 26:01.429
Come on.

26:01.472 --> 26:03.692
- [gasps for air]

26:03.736 --> 26:07.870
- [gasps and sighs]

26:07.914 --> 26:15.095
♪

26:27.977 --> 26:31.546
[alarms beeping]

26:31.590 --> 26:33.635
- Her end-tidal CO2 levels
just went off a cliff.

26:33.679 --> 26:34.897
- It's severe acidosis.

26:34.941 --> 26:36.551
Push two amps of bicarb.

26:36.595 --> 26:39.249
- Removing the shears
caused a pancreatic storm.

26:39.293 --> 26:42.601
- This is not
how she's going out.

26:42.644 --> 26:43.732
Suture.

26:43.776 --> 26:48.041
[alarms beeping]

26:48.084 --> 26:49.695
[drain whooshing]

26:49.738 --> 26:50.870
- Helen?

26:50.913 --> 26:52.393
- Hang on, Max.

26:52.436 --> 26:53.655
- You need--you need to go.

26:53.699 --> 26:54.917
- Not without you.
And if you're not willing

26:54.961 --> 26:56.440
to let go of that pipe,

26:56.484 --> 26:58.965
then I've got
to seal the drain.

26:59.008 --> 27:01.097
- Helen, just go! Please!

27:01.141 --> 27:04.100
I won't, so stop yelling at me.

27:04.144 --> 27:05.145
[slamming]

27:05.188 --> 27:06.581
- What are you doing?

27:06.625 --> 27:08.670
- Weighing down the trash lid
over the drain.

27:10.498 --> 27:12.543
It's working.
- Wait, it's working?

27:12.587 --> 27:14.763
- Give me your hand.
- Are you sure?

27:14.807 --> 27:17.026
- Give me your hand.

27:17.070 --> 27:18.288
Come on.

27:18.332 --> 27:21.378
Come on, watch your step.

27:21.422 --> 27:22.249
Come on.

27:22.292 --> 27:24.904
[metallic groaning]

27:24.947 --> 27:26.949
Lean on there.

27:26.993 --> 27:29.125
[metallic groaning
and squealing]

27:29.169 --> 27:30.431
[elevator dings]

27:30.474 --> 27:33.042
We're almost at the tent.
Just hang on, okay?

27:33.086 --> 27:34.653
He--help!

27:34.696 --> 27:37.438
Can someone help, please!

27:37.481 --> 27:38.439
Help! Oh, Floyd!

27:38.482 --> 27:40.049
Floyd, he's drenched in MFCA.

27:40.093 --> 27:41.268
How are we treating
acute exposure?

27:41.311 --> 27:42.573
- We tried everything.
- And?

27:42.617 --> 27:47.056
- There's no treatment.
Nothing's worked.

27:47.100 --> 27:49.232
- [gasps]

27:50.799 --> 27:53.715
[somber piano tune]

27:53.759 --> 28:00.679
♪

28:09.818 --> 28:11.951
[no audible dialogue]

28:11.994 --> 28:18.044
♪

28:18.087 --> 28:19.872
[no audible dialogue]

28:19.915 --> 28:27.053
♪

28:33.189 --> 28:35.626
[no audible dialogue]

28:35.670 --> 28:42.590
♪

28:57.083 --> 28:59.868
[no audible dialogue]

28:59.912 --> 29:07.049
♪

29:07.093 --> 29:09.269
[no audible dialogue]

29:09.312 --> 29:16.276
♪

29:26.068 --> 29:33.206
♪

29:50.397 --> 29:53.095
[no audible dialogue]

29:53.139 --> 30:00.276
♪

30:30.872 --> 30:31.090
.

30:31.133 --> 30:33.657
- The bolus bicarbonate
and IV saline that you ordered.

30:33.701 --> 30:34.484
- I need CHEM panels drawn
Q15 minutes

30:34.528 --> 30:35.877
until his toxicity is halved.

30:35.921 --> 30:37.270
Q 1 hour after.

30:37.313 --> 30:38.880
- His BP was only 80/50.

30:38.924 --> 30:40.534
- The bicarb will work.
- How can you be so sure?

30:40.577 --> 30:41.840
I'm barely getting a pulse.

30:41.883 --> 30:42.884
- When we removed
the shears from my patient,

30:42.928 --> 30:44.364
it caused a pancreatic storm.

30:44.407 --> 30:46.845
She was going to die,
but then we pushed bicarbonate

30:46.888 --> 30:48.934
to neutralize the acid
in her pancreas.

30:48.977 --> 30:50.283
- Which raised the pH
in her blood,

30:50.326 --> 30:51.806
enhancing excretion.

30:51.850 --> 30:53.721
- Dr. Bloom's
responding to treatment.

30:53.764 --> 30:55.114
- [exhales]

30:55.157 --> 30:58.508
- How did you know
to remove the shears?

30:58.552 --> 31:00.510
- Listened to the universe.

31:00.554 --> 31:03.513
[gentle music]

31:03.557 --> 31:10.694
♪

31:20.791 --> 31:24.143
- Welcome back.

31:24.186 --> 31:27.581
Hey, so, uh, your numbers,
they look great.

31:27.624 --> 31:28.974
You're gonna be fine
by tomorrow.

31:29.017 --> 31:30.932
And don't worry about the ED.

31:30.976 --> 31:32.499
I got it taken care of.

31:32.542 --> 31:34.675
And I'll--

31:34.718 --> 31:39.593
♪

31:39.636 --> 31:41.421
- You can't go to Mt. Zion.

31:41.464 --> 31:43.031
♪

31:43.075 --> 31:45.904
[whispers]
I can't do this without you.

31:45.947 --> 31:47.906
You know that, right?

31:50.691 --> 31:52.693
- Yeah.

31:52.736 --> 31:54.651
I ain't goin' anywhere.

31:54.695 --> 31:57.306
But um, let's just, uh--

31:57.350 --> 32:00.222
let's dial it down a little bit
on the excitement, all right?

32:00.266 --> 32:02.224
I can't take this no more, man.

32:02.268 --> 32:04.618
- Oh, come on.
- [chuckles]

32:04.661 --> 32:06.707
- [chuckles]

32:06.750 --> 32:09.362
- This morning, I was, um--

32:09.405 --> 32:13.975
I was pushing the hope
pretty hard.

32:14.019 --> 32:18.414
And, uh, I was asking
you all to ignore...

32:18.458 --> 32:23.550
everything else.

32:23.593 --> 32:26.031
It's just, it's a weird idea

32:26.074 --> 32:30.470
that positivity can be toxic.

32:30.513 --> 32:33.560
But it absolutely can.

32:33.603 --> 32:36.563
Especially when it comes
at the cost of what is true.

32:36.606 --> 32:40.349
And what is true...

32:40.393 --> 32:45.180
is that nobody wants
to be in this room.

32:45.224 --> 32:46.921
None of you want to be here.

32:46.965 --> 32:48.488
[emotional music]

32:48.531 --> 32:50.664
And no pep talk
that I can give you

32:50.707 --> 32:52.318
will wish that away.

32:52.361 --> 32:56.365
♪

32:56.409 --> 32:58.585
So I wanna
reframe this meeting.

32:58.628 --> 33:04.286
I want to use this time and
this space to tell the truth.

33:04.330 --> 33:06.680
The real truth,
the brutal truth.

33:06.723 --> 33:07.942
I want you to say the things

33:07.986 --> 33:10.031
that you're
not supposed to say.

33:10.075 --> 33:12.251
I'm giving you permission
to say them in here.

33:12.294 --> 33:13.774
The hope that you and your kids

33:13.817 --> 33:15.819
actually need only comes

33:15.863 --> 33:17.560
with that kind of truth, so...

33:17.604 --> 33:20.563
- I keep my gas tank full.

33:20.607 --> 33:23.871
Just in case I, uh,
I can't take it anymore.

33:23.914 --> 33:26.178
♪

33:26.221 --> 33:28.615
And sometimes
I dream about just--

33:28.658 --> 33:29.920
just driving away.

33:29.964 --> 33:31.226
♪

33:31.270 --> 33:32.880
- I sit in the bathroom...

33:32.923 --> 33:34.969
♪

33:35.013 --> 33:37.145
And check prices
on one-way flights.

33:37.189 --> 33:39.626
[voice breaking]
Just knowing I could leave...

33:39.669 --> 33:40.844
- [whispering]
It's okay.

33:40.888 --> 33:42.629
Oh, baby, it's okay.

33:42.672 --> 33:46.154
♪

33:46.198 --> 33:48.635
- I love my daughter.

33:48.678 --> 33:49.766
I do.

33:49.810 --> 33:51.986
♪

33:52.030 --> 33:54.467
But when we're out
in public, she...

33:54.510 --> 33:56.773
♪

33:56.817 --> 33:59.776
She screams and she...

33:59.820 --> 34:01.082
says awful things

34:01.126 --> 34:03.693
and I beg her to stop
and she won't.

34:03.737 --> 34:05.782
And sometimes I...

34:05.826 --> 34:07.958
♪

34:08.002 --> 34:09.351
I hate her.

34:09.395 --> 34:11.092
♪

34:11.136 --> 34:12.833
[tearfully]
What's wrong with me?

34:12.876 --> 34:16.837
[sobbing]

34:16.880 --> 34:20.232
♪

34:20.275 --> 34:22.756
- My son.

34:22.799 --> 34:24.671
He's my miracle.

34:24.714 --> 34:26.542
♪

34:26.586 --> 34:28.675
But sometimes I wish...

34:28.718 --> 34:35.638
♪

34:37.249 --> 34:40.991
[whispering] Sometimes I wish
he hadn't been born.

34:41.035 --> 34:44.256
♪

34:44.299 --> 34:45.474
[sniffles]

34:45.518 --> 34:48.825
♪

34:48.869 --> 34:50.827
Please.

34:50.871 --> 34:55.397
♪

35:00.446 --> 35:07.366
♪

35:09.281 --> 35:12.153
- I woke up at 4:00 a.m.
to bake the cookies.

35:12.197 --> 35:15.243
♪

35:15.287 --> 35:18.116
I wanted them to be fresh
because Alex is here.

35:18.159 --> 35:21.554
♪

35:21.597 --> 35:25.819
And when he threw them
in my face, I...

35:25.862 --> 35:28.952
I swear to God,
I almost hit him.

35:28.996 --> 35:31.651
I would never. I...

35:31.694 --> 35:33.087
of course, I--I...

35:33.131 --> 35:37.091
♪

35:37.135 --> 35:41.835
I just want him to know
how much he hurts me.

35:41.878 --> 35:45.186
[sobbing]
How much I hurt.

35:45.230 --> 35:47.275
♪

35:47.319 --> 35:49.930
It's not his fault.
I shouldn't feel like this.

35:49.973 --> 35:55.762
♪

35:55.805 --> 35:57.764
[sobbing]

35:57.807 --> 36:04.727
♪

36:17.479 --> 36:20.090
[knocking]

36:20.134 --> 36:23.485
♪

36:23.529 --> 36:25.792
- Lyn.

36:25.835 --> 36:27.228
This isn't a bar.

36:29.709 --> 36:30.971
- You said drinks.

36:31.014 --> 36:33.930
[gentle piano music]

36:33.974 --> 36:35.802
♪

36:35.845 --> 36:38.239
- Okay.

36:38.283 --> 36:41.634
You still married?

36:41.677 --> 36:44.114
- It's like this.

36:44.158 --> 36:46.769
My husband and I,

36:46.813 --> 36:50.164
we have this understanding.

36:50.208 --> 36:52.993
When he's out of town,

36:53.036 --> 36:56.518
we're both allowed to...

36:56.562 --> 36:59.782
♪

36:59.826 --> 37:02.872
- [scoffs]

37:02.916 --> 37:06.441
Wow, um...

37:06.485 --> 37:10.837
you obviously...

37:10.880 --> 37:14.232
got a vibe that I dig.

37:14.275 --> 37:17.757
♪

37:17.800 --> 37:21.282
But you also have a ring.

37:21.326 --> 37:24.067
♪

37:24.111 --> 37:28.724
And "understanding" or not,

37:28.768 --> 37:31.249
I can't get down like that.

37:31.292 --> 37:36.079
♪

37:36.123 --> 37:40.214
- It--it's not me, either.

37:40.258 --> 37:42.912
I never actually, um,

37:42.956 --> 37:45.132
acted on it.

37:45.175 --> 37:48.266
I--I just--I thought this
would be easier.

37:48.309 --> 37:50.877
Or at least,
not totally humiliating.

37:50.920 --> 37:54.576
Because I, um,

37:54.620 --> 37:57.013
I dig you, too.

37:57.057 --> 37:58.885
♪

37:58.928 --> 38:00.147
Yeah, so you know what?

38:00.190 --> 38:01.844
I probably should
stop talking right now

38:01.888 --> 38:02.889
so that's what I'm gonna do.

38:02.932 --> 38:04.151
I am going
to stop talking and--

38:04.194 --> 38:06.066
- Hey.

38:06.109 --> 38:07.241
Grab a coat.

38:07.285 --> 38:09.896
♪

38:09.939 --> 38:11.854
- Why?

38:11.898 --> 38:14.161
- You still owe me a drink.

38:14.204 --> 38:16.903
Now it's a double.
- [chuckles]

38:16.946 --> 38:23.823
♪

38:28.610 --> 38:29.611
- Helen?

38:35.661 --> 38:36.705
- Can you see?

38:39.229 --> 38:41.144
- I see you.

38:48.108 --> 38:50.415
What happened?

38:50.458 --> 38:53.548
I remember getting to the tank
and then...

38:57.813 --> 38:58.814
It just goes blank.

39:11.261 --> 39:12.828
- It was just...

39:16.136 --> 39:19.444
Just DECON
and bicarb and stuff.

39:20.749 --> 39:22.360
- Stuff?

39:25.319 --> 39:26.842
- I'm gonna go.

39:26.886 --> 39:29.192
Just gonna let you rest.

39:29.236 --> 39:30.890
- Thanks.

39:35.111 --> 39:37.810
You were there, weren't you?

39:40.421 --> 39:42.815
[gentle music]

39:42.858 --> 39:45.731
♪

39:45.774 --> 39:47.515
I'm sorry.

39:50.083 --> 39:53.434
Guess sometimes...

39:53.478 --> 39:57.003
it takes me a minute...

39:57.046 --> 39:58.439
to remember...

39:58.483 --> 40:02.748
what matters.

40:02.791 --> 40:07.143
More than anything.

40:07.187 --> 40:09.058
You.

40:09.102 --> 40:10.886
♪

40:10.930 --> 40:13.802
- ♪ Well, I tried
to repress it ♪

40:13.846 --> 40:16.805
♪ And I carried its crown

40:16.849 --> 40:20.243
♪ I reached out
to undress it ♪

40:20.287 --> 40:23.682
♪ And love let me down

40:23.725 --> 40:26.641
♪

40:26.685 --> 40:30.428
♪ Love let me down

40:30.471 --> 40:35.694
♪

40:35.737 --> 40:38.697
♪ So I tried to erase it

40:38.740 --> 40:41.177
♪ But the ink bled
right through ♪

40:41.221 --> 40:44.529
♪ Almost drove myself crazy

40:44.572 --> 40:47.967
♪ And these words led to you

40:48.010 --> 40:52.711
♪ And all these
useless dreams ♪

40:52.754 --> 40:55.670
♪ Of living alone

40:55.714 --> 41:00.545
♪ Like a dogless bone

41:00.588 --> 41:07.029
♪ So come let me love you

41:07.073 --> 41:10.990
♪ Come let me love you

41:11.033 --> 41:12.252
♪ And then

41:12.295 --> 41:16.648
[phone ringing]

41:16.691 --> 41:18.824
- I--I didn't know
we still had landlines.

41:18.867 --> 41:20.390
- [chuckles]
- I have to...

41:20.434 --> 41:22.131
give me a sec, sorry.
[clears throat]

41:22.175 --> 41:23.176
Hello, hello?

41:23.219 --> 41:25.178
- Max, we have Luna.

41:25.221 --> 41:26.614
- Oh, thank God, um...

41:26.658 --> 41:28.703
- We heard
what happened to you.

41:28.747 --> 41:30.618
We, uh--
- I have been--

41:30.662 --> 41:32.272
- We're taking her
back home with us.

41:32.315 --> 41:34.056
- Y-yeah, okay.

41:34.100 --> 41:36.406
Great, um, that would
be great, actually.

41:36.450 --> 41:37.451
And I--no, no.

41:37.495 --> 41:39.279
I will--I will pick her up, um,

41:39.322 --> 41:40.280
first thing tomorrow, okay?

41:40.323 --> 41:43.152
- You almost died, Max.

41:43.196 --> 41:44.545
We want her to stay with us.

41:44.589 --> 41:45.938
- That's really not necessary,
Gwen.

41:45.981 --> 41:47.766
I appreciate it but
I'll see you tomorrow, okay?

41:47.809 --> 41:50.029
- No, Max.

41:50.072 --> 41:51.726
We're filing for custody.

41:51.770 --> 41:54.424
[line goes dead]
- Uh...

41:54.468 --> 41:55.817
[stammers]

42:11.920 --> 42:14.880
[ominous music]

42:14.923 --> 42:20.929
♪
